name: Test -> Cables,
description: Test voltage polarity at the end of the control module, outcome="ANOMALOUS\n\nAnalysis:\nThe voltage readings at the control module outputs are nearly identical for both positive ('ctrl_cable_out_pos') and negative ('ctrl_cable_out_neg') cables relative to ground (≈0.36 V and ≈0.0003 V respectively for both polarity measurements). This is not typical, as you would expect a clear voltage differential between the positive and negative output, reflecting correct polarity and output configuration.\n\nThe fact that both the positive and negative terminals are at essentially the same voltage (and both near zero, or both offset by approximately the same amount from ground) may indicate one or more of the following:\n- The cables might be inverted or cross-wired (problem 'CablesInverted'), resulting in no effective voltage difference or reversal.\n- There may be an open circuit, short, or another wiring fault preventing normal voltage output.\n\nRecommended Next Steps:\n- Double check wiring connections for possible inversion or misconnection at both the source and the destination (control module output and receiving side).\n- Using the multimeter, verify voltage directly across the positive and negative terminals (not just relative to ground) to confirm potential difference.\n- Visually inspect for any physical signs of misconnections or damaged cables.\n\nSummary: The results point towards an anomaly in\nCurrent persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:\nNo circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.", precise_action_cost=40.0, cost_breakdown=[('measure_voltage', 20.0), ('measure_voltage', 20.0)], simplified_outcome=None)] 
